   \"installPath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\Zwmar\\\\.openclaw\\\\hooks\\\\living-persona\",\n          \"installedAt\": \"2026-03-23T04:51:02.219Z\",\n          \"hooks\": [\n            \"living-persona\"\n          ]\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  \"channels\": {\n    \"telegram\": {\n      \"enabled\": true,\n      \"configWrites\": true,\n      \"dmPolicy\": \"pairing\",\n      \"botToken\": \"8587631426:AAHvqmo--g25LqsClCWCXj4m617cn2v7V7Q\",\n      \"allowFrom\": [\n        8371302588\n      ],\n      \"groupPolicy\": \"allowlist\",\n      \"streaming\": \"partial\",\n      \"heartbeat\": {\n        \"useIndicator\": false\n      },\n      \"linkPreview\": true\n    }\n  },\n  \"gateway\": {\n    \"port\": 18789,\n    \"mode\": \"local\",\n    \"bind\": \"loopback\",\n    \"auth\": {\n      \"mode\": \"token\",\n      \"token\": \"05a9121e8d27e2ca7f90ec7bab2ddd6b1b111b761aac0fc0\"\n    },\n    \"tailscale\": {\n      \"mode\": \"off\",\n      \"resetOnExit\": false\n    },\n    \"http\": {\n      \"endpoints\": {\n        \"responses\": {\n          \"enabled\": true\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  \"plugins\": {\n    \"allow\": [\n      \"telegram\",\n      \"minimax-portal-auth\"\n    ],\n    \"entries\": {\n      \"minimax-portal-auth\": {\n        \"enabled\": true\n      },\n      \"telegram\": {\n        \"enabled\": true\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774271570531}}
{"type":"message","id":"d4e18500","parentId":"40be3ec4","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:13:11.607Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the config, there's only one channel configured: Telegram. OpenClaw supports different channel types. Let me think about what kind of channel would make sense for the sandbox pulse.\n\nLooking at the config, channels are defined under `channels`. Currently only Telegram is configured. OpenClaw supports various channel types. I could add a separate channel for the sandbox pulse.\n\nThe simplest approach would be to create a dedicated Telegram channel or just use the existing Telegram channel but with a dedicated cron job delivery. But Zach wants a \"new channel.\"\n\nActually, thinking about this more practically - OpenClaw's channel system is for receiving and sending messages through different providers. Adding a new channel means setting up another messaging platform integration. \n\nBut wait - OpenClaw also has webchat support. \n\nI'm realizing that channels in OpenClaw are really about message routing - where to receive from and where to send to. Zach might mean a separate Telegram chat for sandbox updates rather than creating a whole new channel type. But there's no concept of \"chat threads\" in the config - it's just channel providers. The practical options would be creating a new Telegram group with the bot, setting up a different channel type entirely, or just using the existing channel but configuring delivery differently. Looking at the cron job structure, the delivery mode and channel parameters determine where output goes, so I could potentially configure a different channel within the existing Telegram setup.\n\nActually, thinking about this more - the cleanest solution is probably just creating a dedicated cron job that announces to Telegram with a distinct label, which Zach can thread on his end. Or I could set up a new channel entirely, though that would require additional configuration on Zach's part. The simplest path forward is probably just asking what he specifically wants rather than trying to predict whether he means a separate Telegram group, a different messaging platform, or just a logically distinct output stream. I'm looking at the actual cron job delivery structure now - it has `channel`, `to`, and `mode` fields. The config only shows Telegram, so the real question is whether Zach wants a new cron job with a different name and delivery target, or if he's asking me to create an actual new channel provider like Discord or Signal. The simplest interpretation is that he wants a separate cron job just for sandbox pulse updates rather than mixing them with the general background pulse, and the \"new channel\" phrasing is just how he's describing that dedicated output stream.\n\nBut wait - the delivery note says \"delivered\" but Zach is only seeing this in webchat. That's because he's viewing through the OpenClaw control UI, which is essentially a webchat interface that receives messages but doesn't necessarily display Telegram-delivered cron announcements. So if I create a sandbox-specific cron job announcing to Telegram, he might still not see it in webchat. The most straightforward solution is probably just creating that dedicated cron job and delivering to Telegram, then I can relay anything important back to webchat.","thinkingSignature":"7f898332adbece816a8fd0fc17e8f7dcbd8992fc01eeffbf2c9908e926480897"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hxhvf0lz7m54_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw help channel 2>&1 | head -50","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":10066,"output":641,"cacheRead":13593,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":24300,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774271570541}}
{"type":"message","id":"3e67f56e","parentId":"d4e18500","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:13:18.415Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_hxhvf0lz7m54_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\r\n[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\r\n\r\n≡ƒª₧ OpenClaw 2026.3.13 (61d171a) ΓÇö Open source means you can see exactly how I judge your config.\r\n\r\nUsage: openclaw [options] [command]\r\n\r\nOptions:\r\n  --dev                Dev profile: isolate state under ~/.openclaw-dev, default\r\n                       gateway port 19001, and shift derived ports\r\n                       (browser/canvas)\r\n  -h, --help           Display help for command\r\n  --log-level <level>  Global log level override for file + console\r\n                       (silent|fatal|error|warn|info|debug|trace)\r\n  --no-color           Disable ANSI colors\r\n  --profile <name>     Use a named profile (isolates\r\n                       OPENCLAW_STATE_DIR/OPENCLAW_CONFIG_PATH under\r\n                       ~/.openclaw-<name>)\r\n  -V, --version        output the version number\r\n\r\nCommands:\r\n  Hint: commands suffixed with * have subcommands. Run <command> --help for details.\r\n  acp *                Agent Control Protocol tools\r\n  agent                Run one agent turn via the Gateway\r\n  agents *             Manage isolated agents (workspaces, auth, routing)\r\n  approvals *          Manage exec approvals (gateway or node host)\r\n  backup *             Create and verify local backup archives for OpenClaw\r\n                       state\r\n  browser *            Manage OpenClaw's dedicated browser (Chrome/Chromium)\r\n  channels *           Manage connected chat channels (Telegram, Discord, etc.)\r\n  clawbot *            Legacy clawbot command aliases\r\n  completion           Generate shell completion script\r\n  config *             Non-interactive config helpers\r\n                       (get/set/unset/file/validate). Default: starts setup\r\n                       wizard.\r\n  configure            Interactive setup wizard for credentials, channels,\r\n                       gateway, and agent defaults\r\n  cron *               Manage cron jobs via the Gateway scheduler\r\n  daemon *             Gateway service (legacy alias)\r\n  dashboard            Open the Control UI with your current token\r\n  devices *            Device pairing + token management\r\n  directory *          Lookup contact and group IDs (self, peers, groups) for\r\n                       supported chat channels\r\n  dns *                DNS helpers for wide-area discovery (Tailscale + CoreDNS)\r\n  docs                 Search the live OpenClaw docs\r\n  doctor               Health checks + quick fixes for the gateway and channels\r\n  gateway *            Run, inspect, and query the WebSocket Gateway\r\n  health               Fetch health from the running gateway\r\n  help                 Display help for command\r\n  hooks *              Manage internal agent hooks\n\n(Command exited with code 1)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":1,"durationMs":6783,"aggregated":"[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\r\n[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\r\n\r\n≡ƒª₧ OpenClaw 2026.3.13 (61d171a) ΓÇö Open source means you can see exactly how I judge your config.\r\n\r\nUsage: openclaw [options] [command]\r\n\r\nOptions:\r\n  --dev                Dev profile: isolate state under ~/.openclaw-dev, default\r\n                       gateway port 19001, and shift derived ports\r\n                       (browser/canvas)\r\n  -h, --help           Display help for command\r\n  --log-level <level>  Global log level override for file + console\r\n                       (silent|fatal|error|warn|info|debug|trace)\r\n  --no-color           Disable ANSI colors\r\n  --profile <name>     Use a named profile (isolates\r\n                       OPENCLAW_STATE_DIR/OPENCLAW_CONFIG_PATH under\r\n                       ~/.openclaw-<name>)\r\n  -V, --version        output the version number\r\n\r\nCommands:\r\n  Hint: commands suffixed with * have subcommands. Run <command> --help for details.\r\n  acp *                Agent Control Protocol tools\r\n  agent                Run one agent turn via the Gateway\r\n  agents *             Manage isolated agents (workspaces, auth, routing)\r\n  approvals *          Manage exec approvals (gateway or node host)\r\n  backup *             Create and verify local backup archives for OpenClaw\r\n                       state\r\n  browser *            Manage OpenClaw's dedicated browser (Chrome/Chromium)\r\n  channels *           Manage connected chat channels (Telegram, Discord, etc.)\r\n  clawbot *            Legacy clawbot command aliases\r\n  completion           Generate shell completion script\r\n  config *             Non-interactive config helpers\r\n                       (get/set/unset/file/validate). Default: starts setup\r\n                       wizard.\r\n  configure            Interactive setup wizard for credentials, channels,\r\n                       gateway, and agent defaults\r\n  cron *               Manage cron jobs via the Gateway scheduler\r\n  daemon *             Gateway service (legacy alias)\r\n  dashboard            Open the Control UI with your current token\r\n  devices *            Device pairing + token management\r\n  directory *          Lookup contact and group IDs (self, peers, groups) for\r\n                       supported chat channels\r\n  dns *                DNS helpers for wide-area discovery (Tailscale + CoreDNS)\r\n  docs                 Search the live OpenClaw docs\r\n  doctor               Health checks + quick fixes for the gateway and channels\r\n  gateway *            Run, inspect, and query the WebSocket Gateway\r\n  health               Fetch health from the running gateway\r\n  help                 Display help for command\r\n  hooks *              Manage internal agent hooks\n\n(Command exited with code 1)","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774271598404}}
{"type":"message","id":"336d1499","parentId":"3e67f56e","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:13:21.898Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me look at the channels subcommand to understand channel management.","thinkingSignature":"1dff6846e3502959acd57b1663f1c27c2c07548af981f5f74ce0a77d5ea25c77"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_k1x63wzh8o1z_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw channels --help 2>&1","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":11292,"output":57,"cacheRead":13593,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":24942,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774271598416}}
{"type":"message","id":"4c39133b","parentId":"336d1499","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:13:25.466Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_k1x63wzh8o1z_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\n[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\n\n🦞 OpenClaw 2026.3.13 (61d171a) — The lobster in your shell. 🦞\n\nUsage: openclaw channels [options] [command]\n\nManage connected chat channels and accounts\n\nOptions:\n  -h, --help    Display help for command\n\nCommands:\n  add           Add or update a channel account\n  capabilities  Show provider capabilities (intents/scopes + supported features)\n  help          Display help for command\n  list          List configured channels + auth profiles\n  login         Link a channel account (if supported)\n  logout        Log out of a channel session (if supported)\n  logs          Show recent channel logs from the gateway log file\n  remove        Disable or delete a channel account\n  resolve       Resolve channel/user names to IDs\n  status        Show gateway channel status (use status --deep for local)\n\nExamples:\n  openclaw channels list\n    List configured channels and auth profiles.\n  openclaw channels status --probe\n    Run channel status checks and probes.\n  openclaw channels add --channel telegram --token <token>\n    Add or update a channel account non-interactively.\n  openclaw channels login --channel whatsapp\n    Link a WhatsApp Web account.\n\nDocs: https://docs.openclaw.ai/cli/channels"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":3539,"aggregated":"[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\n[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\n\n🦞 OpenClaw 2026.3.13 (61d171a) — The lobster in your shell. 🦞\n\nUsage: openclaw channels [options] [command]\n\nManage connected chat channels and accounts\n\nOptions:\n  -h, --help    Display help for command\n\nCommands:\n  add           Add or update a channel account\n  capabilities  Show provider capabilities (intents/scopes + supported features)\n  help          Display help for command\n  list          List configured channels + auth profiles\n  login         Link a channel account (if supported)\n  logout        Log out of a channel session (if supported)\n  logs          Show recent channel logs from the gateway log file\n  remove        Disable or delete a channel account\n  resolve       Resolve channel/user names to IDs\n  status        Show gateway channel status (use status --deep for local)\n\nExamples:\n  openclaw channels list\n    List configured channels and auth profiles.\n  openclaw channels status --probe\n    Run channel status checks and probes.\n  openclaw channels add --channel telegram --token <token>\n    Add or update a channel account non-interactively.\n  openclaw channels login --channel whatsapp\n    Link a WhatsApp Web account.\n\nDocs: https://docs.openclaw.ai/cli/channels","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774271605454}}
{"type":"message","id":"af9821a8","parentId":"4c39133b","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:13:43.455Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the channels capabilities:\n- openclaw channels add: Add or update a channel account\n- Supported channels: Telegram, Discord, WhatsApp, etc.\n\nBut adding a new channel like Discord would require a bot token and setup. This might be overkill.\n\nLet me think about what Zach actually wants. He wants a \"new channel to deliver it to.\" He sees messages in webchat. The other cron jobs deliver to Telegram.\n\nI think the simplest interpretation is: he wants the sandbox pulse cron to deliver to webchat (the current session) rather than Telegram. That would be a \"new channel\" from his perspective since it's different from the others.\n\n\nBut there's a constraint here - cron jobs with `sessionTarget: \"isolated\"` use `delivery.mode: \"announce\"` which needs a `channel` parameter. The config only has Telegram configured, so if I try to deliver to webchat, it might not work since there's no webchat channel defined in the config.\n\nThe real issue is that the webchat UI he's viewing is the OpenClaw Control UI, which connects to the gateway via websocket, not through a traditional channel. So I'm limited to either delivering to an existing channel like Telegram, or I need to figure out if there's another way to route the cron output to his current session.\n\nLooking at the available channels—Telegram, Discord, WhatsApp, Matrix, and others—setting up Discord would be the most practical option if he wants a dedicated channel for these notifications. But since this is getting complicated, I should probably just ask him directly what he's actually trying to accomplish.\n\nWait, I'm noticing something in the cron job delivery settings—there are different modes like \"announce\", \"webhook\", and \"none\", and for isolated jobs the default is \"announce\". But there's also a \"channel\" parameter that might allow me to route the output differently. The question is whether OpenClaw supports delivering to the current session rather than a specific channel, or if I need to set up an actual messaging platform channel to achieve what he wants.\n\nGiven how convoluted this is getting, I should probably just ask Zach directly what he's trying to accomplish and what platforms he actually uses, since he's currently viewing the webchat but mentioned Telegram works for other cron jobs.","thinkingSignature":"83078c5b22b2c1ebc4d8c3ebd851385b6366c22a8e5f5ce952d962dae0775d56"},{"type":"text","text":"To set up a new *channel* (Telegram bot, Discord, etc.) — yes, I can do that. But it requires a bot token / credentials for whichever platform.\n\nQuick question: what are you actually trying to achieve? A few possibilities:\n\n1. **Separate Telegram chat** — just create a new cron job that announces to your personal Telegram, filtered to sandbox-only content (distinct from the general background pulse)\n2. **Discord/WhatsApp channel** — add a new platform entirely, dedicated to sandbox output\n3. **Webchat** — you're viewing here in the Control UI now; I could deliver the sandbox pulse here instead of routing through Telegram\n\nThe current sandbox pulse runs via Task Scheduler and is completely silent (no delivery). Other cron jobs route to Telegram.\n\nWhat would feel right? And if you want a new platform, do you have a bot token / account ready?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":11662,"output":645,"cacheRead":13593,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":25900,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774271605467}}
