{"type":"message","id":"1159bb5e","parentId":"a038c6ce","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:24:13.343Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking how to add his phone as a node in OpenClaw. Let me check the node-connect skill since that covers this exact topic.","thinkingSignature":"8df919c714ec78f36c848584da08020f4ceb29169287b03dccf9c0084081361d"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hsupoz8fgjfb_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/Zwmar/AppData/Roaming/npm/node_modules/openclaw/skills/node-connect/SKILL.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":80,"cacheRead":25782,"cacheWrite":1115,"totalTokens":27020,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774272247095}}
{"type":"message","id":"078a2059","parentId":"1159bb5e","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:24:13.370Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_hsupoz8fgjfb_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nname: node-connect\ndescription: Diagnose OpenClaw node connection and pairing failures for Android, iOS, and macOS companion apps. Use when QR/setup code/manual connect fails, local Wi-Fi works but VPS/tailnet does not, or errors mention pairing required, unauthorized, bootstrap token invalid or expired, gateway.bind, gateway.remote.url, Tailscale, or plugins.entries.device-pair.config.publicUrl.\n---\n\n# Node Connect\n\nGoal: find the one real route from node -> gateway, verify OpenClaw is advertising that route, then fix pairing/auth.\n\n## Topology first\n\nDecide which case you are in before proposing fixes:\n\n- same machine / emulator / USB tunnel\n- same LAN / local Wi-Fi\n- same Tailscale tailnet\n- public URL / reverse proxy\n\nDo not mix them.\n\n- Local Wi-Fi problem: do not switch to Tailscale unless remote access is actually needed.\n- VPS / remote gateway problem: do not keep debugging `localhost` or LAN IPs.\n\n## If ambiguous, ask first\n\nIf the setup is unclear or the failure report is vague, ask short clarifying questions before diagnosing.\n\nAsk for:\n\n- which route they intend: same machine, same LAN, Tailscale tailnet, or public URL\n- whether they used QR/setup code or manual host/port\n- the exact app text/status/error, quoted exactly if possible\n- whether `openclaw devices list` shows a pending pairing request\n\nDo not guess from `can't connect`.\n\n## Canonical checks\n\nPrefer `openclaw qr --json`. It uses the same setup-code payload Android scans.\n\n```bash\nopenclaw config get gateway.mode\nopenclaw config get gateway.bind\nopenclaw config get gateway.tailscale.mode\nopenclaw config get gateway.remote.url\nopenclaw config get gateway.auth.mode\nopenclaw config get gateway.auth.allowTailscale\nopenclaw config get plugins.entries.device-pair.config.publicUrl\nopenclaw qr --json\nopenclaw devices list\nopenclaw nodes status\n```\n\nIf this OpenClaw instance is pointed at a remote gateway, also run:\n\n```bash\nopenclaw qr --remote --json\n```\n\nIf Tailscale is part of the story:\n\n```bash\ntailscale status --json\n```\n\n## Read the result, not guesses\n\n`openclaw qr --json` success means:\n\n- `gatewayUrl`: this is the actual endpoint the app should use.\n- `urlSource`: this tells you which config path won.\n\nCommon good sources:\n\n- `gateway.bind=lan`: same Wi-Fi / LAN only\n- `gateway.bind=tailnet`: direct tailnet access\n- `gateway.tailscale.mode=serve` or `gateway.tailscale.mode=funnel`: Tailscale route\n- `plugins.entries.device-pair.config.publicUrl`: explicit public/reverse-proxy route\n- `gateway.remote.url`: remote gateway route\n\n## Root-cause map\n\nIf `openclaw qr --json` says `Gateway is only bound to loopback`:\n\n- remote node cannot connect yet\n- fix the route, then generate a fresh setup code\n- `gateway.bind=auto` is not enough if the effective QR route is still loopback\n- same LAN: use `gateway.bind=lan`\n- same tailnet: prefer `gateway.tailscale.mode=serve` or use `gateway.bind=tailnet`\n- public internet: set a real `plugins.entries.device-pair.config.publicUrl` or `gateway.remote.url`\n\nIf `gateway.bind=tailnet set, but no tailnet IP was found`:\n\n- gateway host is not actually on Tailscale\n\nIf `qr --remote requires gateway.remote.url`:\n\n- remote-mode config is incomplete\n\nIf the app says `pairing required`:\n\n- network route and auth worked\n- approve the pending device\n\n```bash\nopenclaw devices list\nopenclaw devices approve --latest\n```\n\nIf the app says `bootstrap token invalid or expired`:\n\n- old setup code\n- generate a fresh one and rescan\n- do this after any URL/auth fix too\n\nIf the app says `unauthorized`:\n\n- wrong token/password, or wrong Tailscale expectation\n- for Tailscale Serve, `gateway.auth.allowTailscale` must match the intended flow\n- otherwise use explicit token/password\n\n## Fast heuristics\n\n- Same Wi-Fi setup + gateway advertises `127.0.0.1`, `localhost`, or loopback-only config: wrong.\n- Remote setup + setup/manual uses private LAN IP: wrong.\n- Tailnet setup + gateway advertises LAN IP instead of MagicDNS / tailnet route: wrong.\n- Public URL set but QR still advertises something else: inspect `urlSource`; config is not what you think.\n- `openclaw devices list` shows pending requests: stop changing network config and approve first.\n\n## Fix style\n\nReply with one concrete diagnosis and one route.\n\nIf there is not enough signal yet, ask for setup + exact app text instead of guessing.\n\nGood:\n\n- `The gateway is still loopback-only, so a node on another network can never reach it. Enable Tailscale Serve, restart the gateway, run openclaw qr again, rescan, then approve the pending device pairing.`\n\nBad:\n\n- `Maybe LAN, maybe Tailscale, maybe port forwarding, maybe public URL.`\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774272253359}}
{"type":"message","id":"08bed301","parentId":"078a2059","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:24:19.395Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The skill is about diagnosing node connection issues. But what Zach needs is the basic setup steps. Let me give him the quick rundown.\n\nFor Android/iOS, OpenClaw has companion apps that connect as nodes. The basic steps are:\n1. Install the OpenClaw app on the phone\n2. Open the app and scan a QR code from the gateway\n3. The gateway needs to be reachable from the phone's network\n\nLet me give him the key steps and check the current gateway config to make sure it's set up to allow node connections.","thinkingSignature":"03f5c20cfce6d2d61aeb1614b65ecb0353c6d5779a91dca6e9808ce8a80cf618"},{"type":"text","text":"Quick steps to add your phone as a node:\n\n**1. On your phone:** Install the OpenClaw companion app (Android/iOS)\n\n**2. On this machine:** Run `openclaw qr` to show the pairing QR code\n\n**3. Scan it with the app**\n\nThat's the basics. But first — let me check if the gateway is even reachable from outside this machine:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_q4xv8jhd71hj_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw qr --json 2>&1","timeout":15}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":14530,"output":235,"cacheRead":13593,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":28358,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774272253371}}
{"type":"message","id":"7ab4d865","parentId":"08bed301","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:24:22.538Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_q4xv8jhd71hj_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\n[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\nError: Gateway is only bound to loopback. Set gateway.bind=lan, enable tailscale serve, or configure plugins.entries.device-pair.config.publicUrl.\n\n(Command exited with code 1)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":1,"durationMs":3117,"aggregated":"[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\n[openclaw] shell env fallback failed: spawnSync /bin/sh ENOENT\nError: Gateway is only bound to loopback. Set gateway.bind=lan, enable tailscale serve, or configure plugins.entries.device-pair.config.publicUrl.\n\n(Command exited with code 1)","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774272262525}}
{"type":"message","id":"0042e5ed","parentId":"7ab4d865","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:24:30.569Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"As I suspected, the gateway is bound to loopback only, which means phones on a different network can't reach it. This is the same issue the skill describes.\n\nFor the phone to connect from outside the LAN, we'd need either:\n1. `gateway.bind=lan` - but that only works if the phone is on the same Wi-Fi\n2. Tailscale serve - if both machines are on Tailscale\n3. A public URL via cloudflared or similar\n\nLet me explain the situation and options.","thinkingSignature":"2467704d6629a815741ead0ee28c4fdd6e5dc5482ad8a1c38c3f721f20f2abc7"},{"type":"text","text":"Here's the issue: the gateway is loopback-only (`127.0.0.1`), so your phone can't reach it from outside this machine right now.\n\nOptions to fix:\n\n**Same Wi-Fi (easiest):**\n```\nopenclaw config set gateway.bind lan\n```\nThis broadcasts the gateway on your LAN — phone just needs to be on the same Wi-Fi. Then run `openclaw qr` and scan.\n\n**Via Tailscale (if you have it):**\n```\nopenclaw config set gateway.bind tailnet\n```\nBoth machines need to be on the same Tailscale tailnet.\n\n**Via cloudflared tunnel (public, persistent URL):**\nYou'd need to set up a persistent Cloudflare tunnel with a domain. The quick tunnel you had before for Telegram works but rotates the URL each time cloudflared restarts.\n\nWhich route works for your setup? Is your phone on the same Wi-Fi, or do you need remote access?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":14853,"output":304,"cacheRead":13593,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":28750,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774272262539}}
{"type":"message","id":"249b8469","parentId":"0042e5ed","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:28:21.573Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Mon 2026-03-23 09:28 EDT] what can i do with remote acess and is it work setting up an old hp laptop with like 6 gigs of ram for you to use as a bare bones kinda home"}],"timestamp":1774272501567}}
{"type":"message","id":"379cee6e","parentId":"249b8469","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:28:40.207Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Two questions:\n1. What can Zach do with remote access to the OpenClaw gateway?\n2. Is an old HP laptop with 6GB RAM worth setting up as a home server for Nova?\n\nLet me think about both:\n\n**Remote access benefits:**\n- Control Nova from anywhere (phone, tablet, other computers)\n- Use the companion app on phone as a full Nova client\n- Access the Control UI from anywhere\n- Could potentially run compute-intensive tasks on that machine\n- Voice interactions if mobile app supports it\n- Could work as a local-only alternative to cloudflare tunnels\n\n**Old HP laptop as a home server with 6GB RAM:**\n- 6GB is quite tight for modern workloads\n\n\n- If it's a basic laptop it could handle OpenClaw gateway + some lightweight services\n- Linux would be better suited than Windows for this use case\n- Ubuntu Server or even a minimal Linux install would be ideal\n- OpenClaw should run fine on it\n- Could potentially run Ollama for local LLM inference, though 6GB limits what models you'd want to use\n- Could serve as aalways-on machine for OpenClaw gateway, cron jobs, scheduled tasks\n- Worth considering whether the power efficiency gains from an older laptop make sense compared to just leaving a desktop running\n\nI should give a balanced perspective on both options.","thinkingSignature":"14c89ed2193bd19159bb36b3479202f6c1a899d93572335e9a1318db811e63ac"},{"type":"text","text":"\n**Remote access (via companion app):**\n- Full Nova UI on your phone — same conversations you have here, but from anywhere\n- Heartbeats and proactive alerts delivered to you wherever you are\n- Could use voice input if the app supports it\n- Basically: Nova in your pocket\n\n**Old HP laptop as a home server:**\nHonestly — yeah, it's a solid idea. 6GB is tight for Windows, but for a Linux bare-bones server it's workable. Things you could run on it:\n\n- OpenClaw gateway as the always-on hub (no desktop needed, just the CLI)\n- Sandbox pulse, cron jobs, background agents — all headless\n- Could run Ollama for local model inference (7B models fit in 6GB)\n- File storage / backup target\n- Could set up Tailscale on it for a persistent VPN into your home network\n\n**Rough plan if you go that route:**\n1. Install Ubuntu Server (minimal, no GUI) — uses ~500MB RAM idle\n2. Install OpenClaw on it\n3. Set `gateway.bind=lan` or `gateway.bind=tailnet` \n4. Your main machine becomes optional — the laptop is always-on and Nova lives there\n5. Phone connects to Nova anywhere via the companion app\n\nThe HP would sip power compared to a desktop. Would be a fun weekend project if you're into that kind of thing."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":567,"cacheRead":27621,"cacheWrite":916,"totalTokens":29147,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774272501572}}
